WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.592 --> 00:00:08.440
DAVID: Thank you all
for coming today.

00:00:08.440 --> 00:00:12.520
We're here with
Morra Aarons-Mele,

00:00:12.520 --> 00:00:14.130
the author of "Hiding
in the Bathroom:

00:00:14.130 --> 00:00:17.500
An Introvert's Roadmap
to Getting Out There

00:00:17.500 --> 00:00:18.820
When You'd Rather Stay Home."

00:00:18.820 --> 00:00:21.340
If I may give a little
bit of a synopsis,

00:00:21.340 --> 00:00:24.130
it's largely about
being an introvert when

00:00:24.130 --> 00:00:28.650
you face things that are
difficult for an introvert.

00:00:28.650 --> 00:00:34.360
It's been easier for many of us
to stay in a corner on our own,

00:00:34.360 --> 00:00:37.120
but Morra's work has
forced her to go out.

00:00:37.120 --> 00:00:38.710
And so she writes
about how to deal

00:00:38.710 --> 00:00:42.310
with this tension, as opposed
to give up and stay away

00:00:42.310 --> 00:00:43.570
from it altogether.

00:00:43.570 --> 00:00:45.290
Please, round of
applause for Morra.

00:00:49.194 --> 00:00:50.824
MORRA AARONS-MELE:
Thanks, David.

00:00:50.824 --> 00:00:51.490
Nice to see you.

00:00:51.490 --> 00:00:53.350
DAVID: How would
you describe being

00:00:53.350 --> 00:00:56.340
an introvert and the challenge
you face as a result of it?

00:00:56.340 --> 00:00:59.710
MORRA AARONS-MELE: I call
myself an ambitious introvert.

00:00:59.710 --> 00:01:03.340
I don't know if that phrase
resonates with any of you.

00:01:03.340 --> 00:01:06.670
I also have a lot of anxieties.

00:01:06.670 --> 00:01:08.560
I have social anxiety.

00:01:08.560 --> 00:01:10.050
I have flying anxiety.

00:01:10.050 --> 00:01:12.760
You know, sometimes for me,
sort of leaving the house

00:01:12.760 --> 00:01:16.120
and going out in the world
can be challenging, especially

00:01:16.120 --> 00:01:18.370
in these times.

00:01:18.370 --> 00:01:22.817
And yet, I run a
business and I chose

00:01:22.817 --> 00:01:25.150
to write this book, which has
taken me out of my comfort

00:01:25.150 --> 00:01:27.910
zone in every way possible.

00:01:27.910 --> 00:01:31.390
Because it's the
manual that I wished

00:01:31.390 --> 00:01:35.650
I had had when I was
trying to build my career.

00:01:35.650 --> 00:01:37.250
I didn't know that
I was an introvert.

00:01:37.250 --> 00:01:39.070
I didn't know that
I had anxiety.

00:01:39.070 --> 00:01:41.200
I just knew that I cried
a lot in the bathroom

00:01:41.200 --> 00:01:42.490
and quit lots of jobs.

00:01:42.490 --> 00:01:45.370
I felt like walking
into the office

00:01:45.370 --> 00:01:49.000
some days was an
assault on my senses.

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:53.600
And you know, as I got
promoted in my career,

00:01:53.600 --> 00:01:56.500
I worked in political consulting
and digital marketing.

00:01:56.500 --> 00:02:00.610
And so as the sort
of demands increased

00:02:00.610 --> 00:02:07.360
to run teams, run meetings,
collaborate, negotiate, sell,

00:02:07.360 --> 00:02:13.060
network, all the stuff
that you really have to do,

00:02:13.060 --> 00:02:13.864
I literally just--

00:02:13.864 --> 00:02:16.280
I felt like it was an assault.
I didn't know how to do it,

00:02:16.280 --> 00:02:17.770
and I didn't have a manual.

00:02:17.770 --> 00:02:19.690
And so instead, I hid
a lot in the bathroom.

00:02:19.690 --> 00:02:21.430
I still hide in
the bathroom a lot.

00:02:21.430 --> 00:02:22.610
I don't know if you do, too.

00:02:22.610 --> 00:02:25.390
I haven't been to
the bathroom here.

00:02:25.390 --> 00:02:30.151
So I wanted to really
provide a really practical--

00:02:30.151 --> 00:02:31.900
if you see the book,
it's super practical.

00:02:31.900 --> 00:02:34.220
There's worksheets,
there's tear sheets.

00:02:34.220 --> 00:02:36.850
And we take on business
development, networking,

00:02:36.850 --> 00:02:39.010
how to survive a professional
networking event.

00:02:39.010 --> 00:02:41.260
That's a huge one.

00:02:41.260 --> 00:02:43.060
Social media, right?

00:02:43.060 --> 00:02:44.295
How do you get out there?

00:02:44.295 --> 00:02:45.920
Everyone says you
should get out there.

00:02:45.920 --> 00:02:48.516
You should have a
personal brand, certainly,

00:02:48.516 --> 00:02:50.140
as you grow in your
career, if you take

00:02:50.140 --> 00:02:51.990
on a more public facing role.

00:02:51.990 --> 00:02:54.715
And this is tough
for some of us.

00:02:54.715 --> 00:02:58.560
DAVID: Most of the crowd
that I see here is engineers.

00:02:58.560 --> 00:03:03.610
But as engineers, every time we
look for a job that's an issue.

00:03:03.610 --> 00:03:07.660
But also, people who are
not software engineers

00:03:07.660 --> 00:03:10.500
don't appreciate how
much collaboration

00:03:10.500 --> 00:03:12.190
is part of the work we do.

00:03:12.190 --> 00:03:16.250
We may be able to get by
with relatively little

00:03:16.250 --> 00:03:19.370
if we only go to the things
that we are called to,

00:03:19.370 --> 00:03:23.130
but if we have an idea we want
to promote, as you're familiar,

00:03:23.130 --> 00:03:24.920
you need to get
someone's attention.

00:03:24.920 --> 00:03:28.640
You need to push an idea
that maybe somebody doesn't

00:03:28.640 --> 00:03:31.990
want to put his attention on.

00:03:31.990 --> 00:03:36.290
And so some of these
things are certainly

00:03:36.290 --> 00:03:39.920
more relevant to us in ways
other than your personal

00:03:39.920 --> 00:03:41.630
experience, directly.

00:03:41.630 --> 00:03:44.360
One of the things you've
described yourself as

00:03:44.360 --> 00:03:45.635
is an ambitious overachiever.

00:03:45.635 --> 00:03:46.990
MORRA AARONS-MELE: Yes.

00:03:46.990 --> 00:03:50.100
No one here is an ambitious
overachiever, I'm sure.

00:03:50.100 --> 00:03:52.670
DAVID: Well, it's easy to
be an overachiever in ways

00:03:52.670 --> 00:03:55.100
that are solitary
with our field,

00:03:55.100 --> 00:03:56.794
until you get into industry.

00:03:56.794 --> 00:03:58.460
When you're in industry,
you aren't just

00:03:58.460 --> 00:04:02.420
writing a program anymore and
then letting the world see it.

00:04:02.420 --> 00:04:04.730
You have to interact
with everybody

00:04:04.730 --> 00:04:09.540
else who your software
is affecting in any way.

00:04:09.540 --> 00:04:15.320
And how do you reconcile
having that urge to achieve

00:04:15.320 --> 00:04:19.850
and facing the fearsome
dog ahead of you

00:04:19.850 --> 00:04:21.697
that you don't want
to interact with?

00:04:21.697 --> 00:04:23.030
MORRA AARONS-MELE: That's right.

00:04:23.030 --> 00:04:25.550
And I think for something
like, I would imagine

00:04:25.550 --> 00:04:27.820
if you've written something--

00:04:27.820 --> 00:04:29.900
I have felt this way
about my passion projects,

00:04:29.900 --> 00:04:31.525
and this is where
introverts can really

00:04:31.525 --> 00:04:33.890
shine if we are
creative people, which

00:04:33.890 --> 00:04:37.170
I believe software engineering
is very creative as well.

00:04:37.170 --> 00:04:41.030
We have the ability
to have faith

00:04:41.030 --> 00:04:44.790
in our project and our work and
to carry it to a certain place.

00:04:44.790 --> 00:04:46.880
So how do you
translate that, not

00:04:46.880 --> 00:04:50.030
only in being able to stand
up in front of a group

00:04:50.030 --> 00:04:53.570
and sell in that vision,
which is an essential skill,

00:04:53.570 --> 00:04:56.480
but be able to negotiate
with other people

00:04:56.480 --> 00:04:58.550
to make your thing come to life?

00:04:58.550 --> 00:05:00.560
And this can be
hard for introverts.

00:05:00.560 --> 00:05:04.220
Sometimes, because we've
gotten feedback in our career,

00:05:04.220 --> 00:05:08.810
even in school, that
we aren't heard, right?

00:05:08.810 --> 00:05:11.060
Because we maybe
talked over a lot.

00:05:11.060 --> 00:05:13.710
I don't know how many
of you have felt that.

00:05:13.710 --> 00:05:15.950
And then of course there
are gender and race and age

00:05:15.950 --> 00:05:17.177
implications and all of that.

00:05:17.177 --> 00:05:19.010
Depending on where
you're at in your career,

00:05:19.010 --> 00:05:22.510
you might get talked
over more or less.

00:05:22.510 --> 00:05:26.360
And so I think one
of the skills that I

00:05:26.360 --> 00:05:28.970
had to learn the hard way, and
that I encourage companies now

00:05:28.970 --> 00:05:33.560
to teach, is how to help
that ambitious introvert

00:05:33.560 --> 00:05:35.360
with an idea.

00:05:35.360 --> 00:05:36.380
Negotiate it.

00:05:36.380 --> 00:05:37.520
Sell it.

00:05:37.520 --> 00:05:39.380
You're not born
learning how to code.

00:05:39.380 --> 00:05:41.000
You're not born
learning how to know

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:43.310
Excel or PowerPoint or Keynote
or any of these things.

00:05:43.310 --> 00:05:44.117
You're taught.

00:05:44.117 --> 00:05:46.700
And so one of the things that I
think we have to seek and give

00:05:46.700 --> 00:05:50.330
in companies is how
to birth your idea

00:05:50.330 --> 00:05:52.160
socially in the office culture.

00:05:52.160 --> 00:05:55.870
DAVID: At Google, many
of us, perhaps not

00:05:55.870 --> 00:05:57.710
a predominant fraction,
but many of us

00:05:57.710 --> 00:06:01.290
have not had a very social
experience before coming here.

00:06:01.290 --> 00:06:04.564
And so many of us are shorter
on those social skills

00:06:04.564 --> 00:06:05.730
and would benefit from them.

00:06:05.730 --> 00:06:08.150
But it sounds like this
is general useful advice

00:06:08.150 --> 00:06:10.335
for companies to help
their employees thrive.

00:06:10.335 --> 00:06:12.710
MORRA AARONS-MELE: And you
have a rich peer culture here,

00:06:12.710 --> 00:06:14.400
which I think can
be really valuable.

00:06:14.400 --> 00:06:17.210
You know, I always say that it's
great to adopt an extrovert.

00:06:17.210 --> 00:06:20.050
If there is someone who
you see has that skill

00:06:20.050 --> 00:06:24.020
set, whether it's being able to
have someone see their vision,

00:06:24.020 --> 00:06:26.810
being able to
negotiate and listen.

00:06:26.810 --> 00:06:29.420
I mean, one of the things that
introverts are really good

00:06:29.420 --> 00:06:31.670
at-- and if you can think
of selling in your software

00:06:31.670 --> 00:06:34.070
project as a sort
of negotiation--

00:06:34.070 --> 00:06:37.520
is it may be tempting
for us to sort of learn

00:06:37.520 --> 00:06:40.290
to go in and tell everyone
about our project.

00:06:40.290 --> 00:06:42.770
But one of, I think, the
natural skills of introverts

00:06:42.770 --> 00:06:45.500
is that we do absorb
and we tune in.

00:06:45.500 --> 00:06:46.832
And so before you sell--

00:06:46.832 --> 00:06:49.040
and I have this in the book
in the chapter on selling

00:06:49.040 --> 00:06:50.390
and negotiate--

00:06:50.390 --> 00:06:51.380
read the room.

00:06:51.380 --> 00:06:53.690
tune in to the other conditions.

00:06:53.690 --> 00:06:54.980
Do your research.

00:06:54.980 --> 00:06:56.910
We're very good at preparing.

00:06:56.910 --> 00:06:59.420
And the layer of sometimes
those of us with anxiety

00:06:59.420 --> 00:07:01.170
makes us prepare even more.

00:07:01.170 --> 00:07:04.470
And so you can learn how to
use your introvert-like super

00:07:04.470 --> 00:07:08.180
powers to actually take a step
back and sell in a project.

00:07:08.180 --> 00:07:12.120
DAVID: You describe yourself
as somewhat of a hermit,

00:07:12.120 --> 00:07:15.350
an introvert, socially anxious.

00:07:15.350 --> 00:07:18.990
I know these aren't synonyms.

00:07:18.990 --> 00:07:20.180
They aren't distinct.

00:07:20.180 --> 00:07:22.520
Could you talk about
where they overlap

00:07:22.520 --> 00:07:24.290
and what the different--
introvert is one

00:07:24.290 --> 00:07:26.442
that I didn't even understand
until a few years ago

00:07:26.442 --> 00:07:27.650
when I learned from a friend.

00:07:27.650 --> 00:07:28.400
MORRA AARONS-MELE:
There's a lot of myths

00:07:28.400 --> 00:07:29.590
about what an introvert is.

00:07:29.590 --> 00:07:31.840
There's a lot of great books
and literature out there,

00:07:31.840 --> 00:07:34.790
and I think it's becoming much
more socialized and acceptable.

00:07:34.790 --> 00:07:38.570
We understand that we are
born probably more introverted

00:07:38.570 --> 00:07:39.890
more extroverted.

00:07:39.890 --> 00:07:41.690
It's not something
that we learn,

00:07:41.690 --> 00:07:43.460
although most
introverts, we learn

00:07:43.460 --> 00:07:45.350
how to fake it at
some point, certainly

00:07:45.350 --> 00:07:48.710
if we're going to go out and
sell or be public in any way.

00:07:48.710 --> 00:07:50.510
I was on "Boston
Public Radio" last week

00:07:50.510 --> 00:07:51.770
and Jim Braude said
to me, well, you

00:07:51.770 --> 00:07:53.690
don't seem like you
suffer from introversion.

00:07:53.690 --> 00:07:55.398
I mean, you can make
eye contact with me.

00:07:55.398 --> 00:07:56.410
And you're laughing.

00:07:56.410 --> 00:07:58.035
I was like, what are
you talking about?

00:08:00.747 --> 00:08:03.080
Introversion doesn't necessarily
mean that you're quiet.

00:08:03.080 --> 00:08:04.952
It doesn't mean even
that you're shy.

00:08:04.952 --> 00:08:06.410
Actually, if you're
shy it may mean

00:08:06.410 --> 00:08:10.310
that you have social anxiety,
or if you're just a little shy.

00:08:10.310 --> 00:08:14.680
An introvert is someone
who needs time and space

00:08:14.680 --> 00:08:18.550
and does great work alone,
who gets that creative energy

00:08:18.550 --> 00:08:19.390
alone.

00:08:19.390 --> 00:08:21.980
And when you go into
overwhelming situations,

00:08:21.980 --> 00:08:23.890
whether it's walking
into a hotel lobby

00:08:23.890 --> 00:08:25.810
with lots of fluorescent
lights and noise,

00:08:25.810 --> 00:08:27.520
or an open plan
office, frankly--

00:08:27.520 --> 00:08:29.500
I mean, I'm obsessed
with open plan offices

00:08:29.500 --> 00:08:31.083
and I have a whole
chapter in the book

00:08:31.083 --> 00:08:34.539
about how to survive an open
plan office or pod situation.

00:08:34.539 --> 00:08:38.320
If you feel like I do,
like you're Superman

00:08:38.320 --> 00:08:40.900
and the kryptonite is
draining your energy,

00:08:40.900 --> 00:08:43.150
you're probably an introvert.

00:08:43.150 --> 00:08:45.580
But it doesn't mean you're
quiet or that you don't talk.

00:08:45.580 --> 00:08:47.560
It just means that
you recharge and you

00:08:47.560 --> 00:08:50.350
need more quiet environment
to do your best work.

00:08:50.350 --> 00:08:52.190
And you like to be
alone with yourself,

00:08:52.190 --> 00:08:53.800
which I think is amazing.

00:08:53.800 --> 00:08:56.620
Social anxiety is another layer
that I talk about in the book

00:08:56.620 --> 00:08:58.210
and that I separate out.

00:08:58.210 --> 00:09:03.580
Because many of us, whether
we're awkward as kids,

00:09:03.580 --> 00:09:05.560
or no one will sit
with us at lunch,

00:09:05.560 --> 00:09:08.140
or we have whatever
kind of trauma,

00:09:08.140 --> 00:09:11.830
we have intense performance
anxiety and fear

00:09:11.830 --> 00:09:13.750
of social situations,
even picking up

00:09:13.750 --> 00:09:16.690
the phone to call a
colleague or a client.

00:09:16.690 --> 00:09:20.080
Walking into a meeting, we
assume people won't like us.

00:09:20.080 --> 00:09:22.330
And again this is
a real challenge

00:09:22.330 --> 00:09:24.460
as you grow in your career
and you have to sell.

00:09:24.460 --> 00:09:26.261
Being a hermit is a--

00:09:26.261 --> 00:09:27.260
I use a tongue in cheek.

00:09:27.260 --> 00:09:28.593
I actually trademarked the term.

00:09:28.593 --> 00:09:30.760
I'm a hermit entrepreneur.

00:09:30.760 --> 00:09:32.780
And this is my choice.

00:09:32.780 --> 00:09:35.530
I left corporate America
about 10 years ago,

00:09:35.530 --> 00:09:38.710
and decided that I was
going to work for myself.

00:09:38.710 --> 00:09:41.500
I started a small business,
successful business,

00:09:41.500 --> 00:09:43.150
small business.

00:09:43.150 --> 00:09:46.420
I decided I didn't want to
become a corporate executive.

00:09:46.420 --> 00:09:49.480
I didn't want to have a big
career in the typical sense.

00:09:49.480 --> 00:09:52.390
I was willing to make less
money and have less power

00:09:52.390 --> 00:09:54.670
systemically, because it
is that important to me

00:09:54.670 --> 00:09:55.780
to work from home.

00:09:55.780 --> 00:09:58.210
I mean, that sounds
ridiculous, but it really is.

00:09:58.210 --> 00:09:59.500
I love to work from home.

00:09:59.500 --> 00:10:01.060
I like to be by myself.

00:10:01.060 --> 00:10:02.890
My favorite day--
and this may not

00:10:02.890 --> 00:10:05.111
apply to you-- is a
day without meetings.

00:10:05.111 --> 00:10:06.610
I mean, we were
talking about email.

00:10:06.610 --> 00:10:09.340
Email is also a big sensory
overload for a lot of us.

00:10:09.340 --> 00:10:12.100
But a day without meetings,
and time to think.

00:10:12.100 --> 00:10:14.110
And so I created a
business that allows

00:10:14.110 --> 00:10:17.530
me to build in days
alone, time to think,

00:10:17.530 --> 00:10:19.230
and then I hit the road.

00:10:19.230 --> 00:10:22.660
DAVID: How do you reconcile
being a mother of three

00:10:22.660 --> 00:10:25.944
with having time alone at home?

00:10:25.944 --> 00:10:28.240
MORRA AARONS-MELE:
It's hard, you know.

00:10:28.240 --> 00:10:30.340
But I actually-- I
mean, oh god, this

00:10:30.340 --> 00:10:34.450
feels horrible to admit--
but I build in my alone time

00:10:34.450 --> 00:10:35.670
during my work day.

00:10:35.670 --> 00:10:38.050
Because your kids
don't care, right?

00:10:38.050 --> 00:10:40.060
Your kids don't care
if you need a break.

00:10:40.060 --> 00:10:43.060
So what I try to do
is I try to protect

00:10:43.060 --> 00:10:47.920
my time during the workweek,
actually, to get a lot of time

00:10:47.920 --> 00:10:48.970
to think.

00:10:48.970 --> 00:10:51.714
And I justify it
by actually saying

00:10:51.714 --> 00:10:52.880
it helps me run my business.

00:10:52.880 --> 00:10:54.213
It's where I have my best ideas.

00:10:54.213 --> 00:10:55.690
It's where I come
up with solutions

00:10:55.690 --> 00:10:59.010
and figure out how to pay for
things and hire new people.

00:10:59.010 --> 00:11:00.426
But, yes.

00:11:00.426 --> 00:11:02.972
DAVID: One of the complications
of working at home-- parent.

00:11:02.972 --> 00:11:03.930
MORRA AARONS-MELE: Yes.

00:11:03.930 --> 00:11:06.130
Not everyone is made
to work from home.

00:11:06.130 --> 00:11:07.250
It's a discipline.

00:11:07.250 --> 00:11:09.640
I don't know if you have a
work from home policy here.

00:11:09.640 --> 00:11:11.080
I think that some
people really seek it,

00:11:11.080 --> 00:11:12.621
and some people it
drives them crazy.

00:11:12.621 --> 00:11:14.320
DAVID: We were
talking earlier about

00:11:14.320 --> 00:11:17.830
how social anxiety
and introversion can

00:11:17.830 --> 00:11:20.890
be different for women than
men, broadly, of course.

00:11:20.890 --> 00:11:22.840
It's not going to be
the same in every case.

00:11:22.840 --> 00:11:25.090
Could you talk some
about how it differs

00:11:25.090 --> 00:11:29.374
for women in ways that might
not be obvious to us or not?

00:11:29.374 --> 00:11:30.790
MORRA AARONS-MELE:
I mean, I think

00:11:30.790 --> 00:11:33.165
one of the things that has
been really remarkable to me--

00:11:33.165 --> 00:11:36.010
and I love seeing so many men
here today-- is, you know,

00:11:36.010 --> 00:11:38.292
I wrote the book sort
of geared towards women

00:11:38.292 --> 00:11:39.250
because that's my bias.

00:11:39.250 --> 00:11:41.200
I run a business
called women online

00:11:41.200 --> 00:11:43.270
and I create political
and social marketing

00:11:43.270 --> 00:11:45.130
campaigns that mobilize women.

00:11:45.130 --> 00:11:47.050
But I think what's
interesting is

00:11:47.050 --> 00:11:53.380
that men feel work-life
conflict, the tug between home,

00:11:53.380 --> 00:11:55.340
work, the pressure.

00:11:55.340 --> 00:11:57.730
Certainly-- I mean, this is
one thing I talk a lot about

00:11:57.730 --> 00:12:00.430
in the book when you think
of sales and negotiating,

00:12:00.430 --> 00:12:03.070
and again it's a bit different
maybe in an environment like

00:12:03.070 --> 00:12:05.200
this, but you will come
up against it I think--

00:12:05.200 --> 00:12:07.634
to be that sort of
alpha male salesman.

00:12:07.634 --> 00:12:09.550
That's something that
women don't really face.

00:12:09.550 --> 00:12:11.470
We face a lot of other biases.

00:12:11.470 --> 00:12:13.270
But I've heard from
many introverted men

00:12:13.270 --> 00:12:15.317
at work who feel
really frustrated.

00:12:15.317 --> 00:12:16.150
One guy said to me--

00:12:16.150 --> 00:12:17.650
I gave a talk last
week in Cambridge

00:12:17.650 --> 00:12:20.860
and he said, how did the
extroverts when everything?

00:12:20.860 --> 00:12:26.000
He felt in his work experience
that because he was more quiet,

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:30.130
he was not your typical sort get
out there kind of glad handler,

00:12:30.130 --> 00:12:32.650
that he felt he didn't fit
in at his office, which

00:12:32.650 --> 00:12:34.420
I felt was really sad for him.

00:12:34.420 --> 00:12:39.040
So I think for men there
are barriers to feeling--

00:12:39.040 --> 00:12:40.980
certainly if you do like
me, you're a hermit.

00:12:40.980 --> 00:12:42.280
You love to work from home.

00:12:42.280 --> 00:12:43.870
You like alone time.

00:12:43.870 --> 00:12:46.120
You don't maybe want to go
out and take clients out

00:12:46.120 --> 00:12:48.800
for drinks or dinner or
sell in all those ways.

00:12:48.800 --> 00:12:49.780
That's a barrier.

00:12:49.780 --> 00:12:53.620
For women, if we are
more introverted,

00:12:53.620 --> 00:12:57.460
data show we are less
likely to get promoted.

00:12:57.460 --> 00:12:59.110
We earn less money,
and of course women

00:12:59.110 --> 00:13:03.970
earn less money anyway, and
we fight to get heard anyway.

00:13:03.970 --> 00:13:08.260
So there's really a
double barreled assault

00:13:08.260 --> 00:13:11.980
on women, I think,
who, again, may not

00:13:11.980 --> 00:13:15.950
present in a typical
leadership fashion.

00:13:15.950 --> 00:13:18.980
You know, you only have to look
at our politics to see right

00:13:18.980 --> 00:13:21.740
now-- and I promised I wouldn't
get political but I can't help

00:13:21.740 --> 00:13:22.460
it--

00:13:22.460 --> 00:13:27.200
that too often, the salesperson
in chief wins in our culture.

00:13:27.200 --> 00:13:30.620
Certainly, when it comes to
what we see as leadership.

00:13:30.620 --> 00:13:33.590
I could not help feeling
all during the election

00:13:33.590 --> 00:13:35.690
that Hillary Clinton
is really an introvert,

00:13:35.690 --> 00:13:38.720
and if she could just sell
her policies in small groups

00:13:38.720 --> 00:13:41.990
and connect in an
authentic way, things

00:13:41.990 --> 00:13:43.310
would be so much different.

00:13:43.310 --> 00:13:46.040
And yet we got the sort of man
in front of the room talking

00:13:46.040 --> 00:13:46.912
and selling.

00:13:46.912 --> 00:13:48.620
And I think that that's
powerful and that

00:13:48.620 --> 00:13:51.206
extends to every
corporate environment

00:13:51.206 --> 00:13:52.580
and every leadership
environment.

00:13:52.580 --> 00:13:55.190
We need to think about
that, and gender is a piece.

00:13:55.190 --> 00:14:02.900
DAVID: You wrote that you
would be more successful if you

00:14:02.900 --> 00:14:04.297
went to cocktail parties more.

00:14:04.297 --> 00:14:05.880
MORRA AARONS-MELE:
37% more successful

00:14:05.880 --> 00:14:07.129
if I went to cocktail parties.

00:14:07.129 --> 00:14:08.420
DAVID: Could you explain that?

00:14:08.420 --> 00:14:09.670
MORRA AARONS-MELE: Absolutely.

00:14:09.670 --> 00:14:13.940
I mean, I think
it's amazing, now,

00:14:13.940 --> 00:14:16.700
that we have so many
online tools to network.

00:14:16.700 --> 00:14:19.790
And I talk about that
a lot in the book.

00:14:19.790 --> 00:14:23.890
In many, many
business environments,

00:14:23.890 --> 00:14:27.040
we are obsessed with networking.

00:14:27.040 --> 00:14:29.500
I call it an "enlightened bro."

00:14:29.500 --> 00:14:32.920
There are guys like Gary
Vaynerchuk and Tim Ferriss

00:14:32.920 --> 00:14:36.430
out there, and they're full
of tips to solve your life.

00:14:36.430 --> 00:14:39.400
But if you watch any
leadership video on YouTube,

00:14:39.400 --> 00:14:42.790
chances are there is going to
be something about getting out

00:14:42.790 --> 00:14:45.940
there, about networking, still
the old chestnuts of never

00:14:45.940 --> 00:14:47.260
eating lunch alone--

00:14:47.260 --> 00:14:49.270
again, prevalent in our culture.

00:14:49.270 --> 00:14:52.390
And if you're like me and
you're sort of allergic to this,

00:14:52.390 --> 00:14:56.402
and you go to a professional
conference and think,

00:14:56.402 --> 00:14:58.610
oh gosh, how am I going to
survive the cocktail hour?

00:14:58.610 --> 00:15:00.710
I just want to go back to
my hotel room and hide,

00:15:00.710 --> 00:15:02.530
or whatever meet up
group, or whatever

00:15:02.530 --> 00:15:04.540
you're part of to sort
of advance your career,

00:15:04.540 --> 00:15:06.400
and you know it's important.

00:15:06.400 --> 00:15:08.920
Again, you can always
feel like you're at odds.

00:15:08.920 --> 00:15:10.662
So I probably would
be more successful

00:15:10.662 --> 00:15:12.370
if I liked networking
more, but I've also

00:15:12.370 --> 00:15:13.360
made my peace with it.

00:15:13.360 --> 00:15:16.750
And that's why for me,
blogging and participating

00:15:16.750 --> 00:15:19.630
in online community has
been a savior, because I

00:15:19.630 --> 00:15:21.491
can find connections online.

00:15:21.491 --> 00:15:23.740
I can blog and connect with
people who care about what

00:15:23.740 --> 00:15:26.200
I do, and it doesn't
matter if we're

00:15:26.200 --> 00:15:29.320
going for drinks at the local
Hilton on a Tuesday night.

00:15:29.320 --> 00:15:30.910
DAVID: You communicate
on your terms.

00:15:30.910 --> 00:15:33.220
MORRA AARONS-MELE: I communicate
on my terms from bed.

00:15:33.220 --> 00:15:34.740
DAVID: Instead of party terms.

00:15:37.280 --> 00:15:40.510
You hinted at having
advice for people,

00:15:40.510 --> 00:15:42.100
for the most important
thing that they

00:15:42.100 --> 00:15:43.860
could do when at parties.

00:15:43.860 --> 00:15:46.220
Could you explain that?

00:15:46.220 --> 00:15:47.440
I was curious what it was.

00:15:47.440 --> 00:15:48.050
MORRA AARONS-MELE: Yes.

00:15:48.050 --> 00:15:49.549
Well, the last
chapter of the book--

00:15:49.549 --> 00:15:52.240
and actually if you go on
hidinginthebathroom.com,

00:15:52.240 --> 00:15:55.270
I have a 16 point guide
to getting out there

00:15:55.270 --> 00:15:56.740
when you have to.

00:15:56.740 --> 00:16:02.020
And one of the things
that I talk about is--

00:16:02.020 --> 00:16:04.580
and again, this is
simple advice but it's

00:16:04.580 --> 00:16:06.790
really, really powerful--

00:16:06.790 --> 00:16:10.270
is that feeling of
anticipatory anxiety

00:16:10.270 --> 00:16:12.580
when you have to walk
into a networking event,

00:16:12.580 --> 00:16:15.850
or you have to go to a
presentation or meet a new team

00:16:15.850 --> 00:16:17.770
or whatever you feel.

00:16:17.770 --> 00:16:19.990
I think it's really important
to sort of physically

00:16:19.990 --> 00:16:21.010
get a sense of yourself.

00:16:21.010 --> 00:16:23.500
You know, actors do this
before they get on stage.

00:16:23.500 --> 00:16:25.361
They check in with themselves.

00:16:25.361 --> 00:16:26.860
They check in with
their motivation.

00:16:26.860 --> 00:16:28.610
Why am I here?

00:16:28.610 --> 00:16:29.675
I feel that all the time.

00:16:29.675 --> 00:16:30.550
I want to be at home.

00:16:30.550 --> 00:16:31.142
Why am I here?

00:16:31.142 --> 00:16:32.850
I don't want to go on
this business trip.

00:16:32.850 --> 00:16:33.874
I'm scared.

00:16:33.874 --> 00:16:35.290
I don't want to
walk in this room.

00:16:35.290 --> 00:16:36.040
Why am I here?

00:16:36.040 --> 00:16:38.230
Sometimes it's as simple
as I have to pay the bills.

00:16:38.230 --> 00:16:39.160
That's legit.

00:16:39.160 --> 00:16:40.970
Sometimes it's I
care about my work.

00:16:40.970 --> 00:16:42.760
I want to share
what I've written.

00:16:42.760 --> 00:16:43.690
I want to bring this.

00:16:43.690 --> 00:16:47.080
So checking into the meaning
and checking into your body.

00:16:47.080 --> 00:16:49.330
For me, also-- and I don't
know, this is different

00:16:49.330 --> 00:16:50.420
for everyone--

00:16:50.420 --> 00:16:52.262
I have clothes that I wear.

00:16:52.262 --> 00:16:53.720
Literally, I'll
put my lipstick on.

00:16:53.720 --> 00:16:56.139
I will put on my armor
and become the person

00:16:56.139 --> 00:16:57.430
who would play me in the movie.

00:16:57.430 --> 00:17:01.210
Because I can then get
that person out there.

00:17:01.210 --> 00:17:04.300
And then I follow what my
friend Dr. Ellen Hendrickson

00:17:04.300 --> 00:17:05.859
calls the 10 second rule.

00:17:05.859 --> 00:17:07.111
She's a social psychologist.

00:17:07.111 --> 00:17:08.569
You can do anything
for 10 seconds.

00:17:08.569 --> 00:17:11.079
You can even put your feet
over fire for 10 seconds.

00:17:11.079 --> 00:17:13.210
So just give yourself that push.

00:17:13.210 --> 00:17:17.260
Walk into the room or walk
up to someone and say, hi.

00:17:17.260 --> 00:17:19.900
And then muscle
memory takes over.

00:17:19.900 --> 00:17:21.200
The other tip that I have--

00:17:21.200 --> 00:17:22.990
and this is one that I actually
talked to a lot of people

00:17:22.990 --> 00:17:23.489
about.

00:17:23.489 --> 00:17:24.819
You'll hear this a lot.

00:17:24.819 --> 00:17:26.619
I call it channeling
your inner Oprah,

00:17:26.619 --> 00:17:28.207
but some people play journalist.

00:17:28.207 --> 00:17:30.040
You know, especially
if you're an introvert,

00:17:30.040 --> 00:17:31.840
you don't like the spotlight.

00:17:31.840 --> 00:17:32.800
Ask people questions.

00:17:32.800 --> 00:17:35.770
Again, tune in to other people.

00:17:35.770 --> 00:17:38.980
You don't have to be the
best conversationalist

00:17:38.980 --> 00:17:41.657
to be remembered as a
great conversationalist.

00:17:41.657 --> 00:17:43.240
Because if you're
present with someone

00:17:43.240 --> 00:17:47.550
and you can ask them questions,
they'll think that you are.

00:17:47.550 --> 00:17:49.360
Anyway, I have lots
of other good tips,

00:17:49.360 --> 00:17:51.880
but one thing I
also wanted to say

00:17:51.880 --> 00:17:54.850
is to give yourself a reward.

00:17:54.850 --> 00:17:56.620
This is something
that you can think of,

00:17:56.620 --> 00:17:58.460
if you're at a
professional conference--

00:17:58.460 --> 00:18:00.130
did you know that
there, I think it's

00:18:00.130 --> 00:18:04.610
137 professional
conferences in the US a day?

00:18:04.610 --> 00:18:06.850
It is the most booming industry.

00:18:06.850 --> 00:18:09.970
And so again, the way that
we're taught now, to network

00:18:09.970 --> 00:18:11.530
more than ever,
we're also expected

00:18:11.530 --> 00:18:13.696
to go to conferences more
than ever, which is weird.

00:18:13.696 --> 00:18:16.180
I mean, certainly in tech,
conferences are out of control,

00:18:16.180 --> 00:18:16.960
right?

00:18:16.960 --> 00:18:21.810
So for me, I'll do my research
about who I want to meet.

00:18:21.810 --> 00:18:23.560
I'll say I got to
meet three people.

00:18:23.560 --> 00:18:25.087
And then I let myself leave.

00:18:25.087 --> 00:18:26.670
Sometimes I'll go
hide in the bathroom

00:18:26.670 --> 00:18:28.045
or I'll go hide
in my hotel room.

00:18:28.045 --> 00:18:28.630
And it's OK.

00:18:28.630 --> 00:18:29.539
DAVID: Set a quota.

00:18:29.539 --> 00:18:30.830
MORRA AARONS-MELE: Set a quota.

00:18:30.830 --> 00:18:32.442
Set a goal.

00:18:32.442 --> 00:18:35.500
DAVID: There's a
term that you used--

00:18:35.500 --> 00:18:37.332
I didn't get to the
part of the book

00:18:37.332 --> 00:18:39.790
where you explain this term,
but I'm curious what it means.

00:18:39.790 --> 00:18:41.050
You mention achievement porn.

00:18:41.050 --> 00:18:42.800
MORRA AARONS-MELE:
Achievement porn, yeah.

00:18:42.800 --> 00:18:43.545
DAVID: Could you explain that?

00:18:43.545 --> 00:18:45.160
MORRA AARONS-MELE: A while
back, I wrote an article

00:18:45.160 --> 00:18:47.118
in "The Harvard Business
Review" about the rise

00:18:47.118 --> 00:18:48.175
of entrepreneurship porn.

00:18:51.130 --> 00:18:53.520
I'm glad you think it's funny.

00:18:53.520 --> 00:18:57.470
I have been a sort of player
on the edges of the Boston tech

00:18:57.470 --> 00:18:59.500
and VC scene, and
those sort of women

00:18:59.500 --> 00:19:03.460
in tech scene for many
years now, and then in LA.

00:19:03.460 --> 00:19:06.580
And it's very sexy to
be an entrepreneur.

00:19:06.580 --> 00:19:08.980
It's very sexy to
work at a startup.

00:19:08.980 --> 00:19:11.320
It's probably still
sexy to work at Google.

00:19:11.320 --> 00:19:13.390
You know, so you guys have that.

00:19:13.390 --> 00:19:15.665
But as you know,
from your friends,

00:19:15.665 --> 00:19:18.040
whenever you work at a startup
or if you found a startup,

00:19:18.040 --> 00:19:18.830
it's very sexy.

00:19:18.830 --> 00:19:19.954
People want to talk to you.

00:19:19.954 --> 00:19:21.570
You're an entrepreneur, right?

00:19:21.570 --> 00:19:24.030
And so the media, and
networking culture,

00:19:24.030 --> 00:19:26.820
and leadership talks, and
this whole conference industry

00:19:26.820 --> 00:19:30.330
has really glamorized
entrepreneurship, especially

00:19:30.330 --> 00:19:32.400
tech entrepreneurship, right?

00:19:32.400 --> 00:19:35.760
It's made it seem like that's
what we should aspire to,

00:19:35.760 --> 00:19:40.350
and scaling, and never sleeping,
and tirelessly fighting

00:19:40.350 --> 00:19:42.990
until we get funded or we grow.

00:19:42.990 --> 00:19:46.320
And I call it porn, because
you know it when you see it.

00:19:46.320 --> 00:19:49.770
You read all these profiles of
these young entrepreneurs who

00:19:49.770 --> 00:19:52.110
would stop at nothing and
made a gazillion dollars.

00:19:52.110 --> 00:19:55.404
Very few of us can do that,
even if we're smart enough.

00:19:55.404 --> 00:19:56.820
For me, personally,
and the people

00:19:56.820 --> 00:19:58.611
that I interview in my
book and my podcast,

00:19:58.611 --> 00:20:00.540
they didn't want to do that.

00:20:00.540 --> 00:20:03.420
Some of us wanted to have really
great lifestyle businesses.

00:20:03.420 --> 00:20:06.490
We needed to step back from
the entrepreneurship porn,

00:20:06.490 --> 00:20:07.740
and the achievement porn, too.

00:20:07.740 --> 00:20:09.540
You know, it's this
sense that if you

00:20:09.540 --> 00:20:13.080
don't give 110%
every single day,

00:20:13.080 --> 00:20:15.160
you're letting the side down.

00:20:15.160 --> 00:20:16.452
DAVID: So it's the false image.

00:20:16.452 --> 00:20:18.118
MORRA AARONS-MELE:
It's the false image.

00:20:18.118 --> 00:20:19.080
It's the glossy image.

00:20:19.080 --> 00:20:21.750
Even failure is
sort of glamorized,

00:20:21.750 --> 00:20:24.930
because we read a lot of
stories about these sort of epic

00:20:24.930 --> 00:20:27.910
failures, certainly in
Silicon Valley and New York.

00:20:27.910 --> 00:20:30.180
But they never really
feel like failures to me.

00:20:30.180 --> 00:20:31.846
I don't know about
you, but they sort of

00:20:31.846 --> 00:20:34.480
feel like just a blip in the
road till the next big one.

00:20:34.480 --> 00:20:36.180
And life isn't like that.

00:20:36.180 --> 00:20:40.140
DAVID: You mentioned the
tech industry's passion

00:20:40.140 --> 00:20:45.270
for an entrepreneur who drives
an idea and starts a company.

00:20:45.270 --> 00:20:48.480
But I feel like we're changing
more broadly than that.

00:20:48.480 --> 00:20:54.010
More and more people are
expected to make their job,

00:20:54.010 --> 00:20:56.760
as you've done, even
without building a company,

00:20:56.760 --> 00:21:01.830
just as a sole contributor who
is also the CEO of the company,

00:21:01.830 --> 00:21:04.240
you might say.

00:21:04.240 --> 00:21:08.130
And that requires a lot of
social networking of sorts

00:21:08.130 --> 00:21:11.490
as well, a lot of
often cold calling

00:21:11.490 --> 00:21:14.250
to start a business that doesn't
exist because no one else

00:21:14.250 --> 00:21:17.100
has done it for you.

00:21:17.100 --> 00:21:20.510
Given that many of us,
well maybe not in this room

00:21:20.510 --> 00:21:22.650
this year, but many
of the people watching

00:21:22.650 --> 00:21:24.360
this may find
themselves in that state

00:21:24.360 --> 00:21:25.830
while looking for
their next job,

00:21:25.830 --> 00:21:28.200
finding that they need
to make it themselves.

00:21:28.200 --> 00:21:33.790
If they prepare themselves
to walk into that room,

00:21:33.790 --> 00:21:35.710
then they're talking
to the people

00:21:35.710 --> 00:21:38.080
and their nerve fails them.

00:21:38.080 --> 00:21:40.840
Do you have any advice
for how to pull yourself

00:21:40.840 --> 00:21:45.632
back together when you feel
you're not up to the task?

00:21:45.632 --> 00:21:47.590
MORRA AARONS-MELE: I
mean, I think, it's again,

00:21:47.590 --> 00:21:50.290
it's about tapping into the
meaning and the motivation.

00:21:50.290 --> 00:21:52.480
I like to use the metaphor
of being a crafts person.

00:21:52.480 --> 00:21:54.179
You know, if you
had built a house

00:21:54.179 --> 00:21:56.470
that this really lovely family
were going to move into,

00:21:56.470 --> 00:21:59.170
and you had lovingly taken
care of every element,

00:21:59.170 --> 00:22:00.820
you would be proud
to talk about it.

00:22:00.820 --> 00:22:04.012
I'm a big fan of
freelancing and consulting,

00:22:04.012 --> 00:22:06.220
although there are many
things that are bad about it,

00:22:06.220 --> 00:22:08.050
and you probably
will make less money.

00:22:08.050 --> 00:22:10.180
You will have maybe less
of a systemic impact.

00:22:10.180 --> 00:22:12.310
You've got to think
about health care.

00:22:12.310 --> 00:22:16.060
But for many of those people,
or you, in five years from now,

00:22:16.060 --> 00:22:18.310
if you leave this place
and go walk into a room

00:22:18.310 --> 00:22:21.700
to make it on your own, even
if it is as a consultant,

00:22:21.700 --> 00:22:24.190
don't feel like you
need to start afresh.

00:22:24.190 --> 00:22:28.090
Often your best clients will
be your old company, the people

00:22:28.090 --> 00:22:29.770
that used to work for.

00:22:29.770 --> 00:22:34.180
An introverts gift is
actually managing a network

00:22:34.180 --> 00:22:37.155
in a way that is good for us.

00:22:37.155 --> 00:22:38.530
And so I find that
we're actually

00:22:38.530 --> 00:22:40.480
good at sustaining those
long relationships.

00:22:40.480 --> 00:22:43.370
I have a rule called the 10
touches, which is in the book.

00:22:43.370 --> 00:22:46.520
I learned it from my husband,
my favorite adopted extrovert.

00:22:46.520 --> 00:22:50.800
But for me, I can handle 10
business development touches

00:22:50.800 --> 00:22:51.520
a week.

00:22:51.520 --> 00:22:54.100
It might be just dropping you
an email, which I know now

00:22:54.100 --> 00:22:56.980
you won't see, but that's OK.

00:22:56.980 --> 00:22:58.330
It could be calling someone.

00:22:58.330 --> 00:23:01.420
It could be recommending
someone on LinkedIn,

00:23:01.420 --> 00:23:03.400
making some sort
of outward gesture.

00:23:03.400 --> 00:23:06.040
I can do all of this
from my home office.

00:23:06.040 --> 00:23:08.740
But if I have the discipline
of reaching out to 10 people

00:23:08.740 --> 00:23:10.690
a week, and you can
do this actually

00:23:10.690 --> 00:23:13.840
while you're working for someone
else to help build that network

00:23:13.840 --> 00:23:17.290
and help build that future
network of potential employers,

00:23:17.290 --> 00:23:20.520
funders, colleagues,
staff, whatever--

00:23:20.520 --> 00:23:23.380
you know, I'm a big believer
in breaking things down

00:23:23.380 --> 00:23:25.220
into bit-sized chunks,
bearable chunks.

00:23:25.220 --> 00:23:27.940
So I do the 10
touches every week.

00:23:27.940 --> 00:23:30.820
I keep my network
going, and so then I'm

00:23:30.820 --> 00:23:32.680
never so scared to
walk into a room,

00:23:32.680 --> 00:23:34.780
because I know why I'm there.

00:23:34.780 --> 00:23:38.650
I try to have a sense that
I am not alone in this work,

00:23:38.650 --> 00:23:39.600
if that makes sense.

00:23:39.600 --> 00:23:41.110
DAVID: Thank you very much.

00:23:41.110 --> 00:23:43.060
Is this a good time
for questions from the

00:23:43.060 --> 00:23:44.060
MORRA AARONS-MELE: Sure.

00:23:44.060 --> 00:23:44.620
Sure thing.

