AUDIENCE: Oh, hi, Morra.

00:25:52.180 --> 00:25:53.096
MORRA AARONS-MELE: Hi.

00:25:53.096 --> 00:25:56.064
AUDIENCE: So you
talked about creating

00:25:56.064 --> 00:25:58.230
sort of like, space and
alone time in the businesses

00:25:58.230 --> 00:25:58.730
you create.

00:25:58.730 --> 00:26:00.970
Do you have recommendations
for how to do that

00:26:00.970 --> 00:26:02.530
within a corporate environment?

00:26:02.530 --> 00:26:04.567
Given that we are
in an open layout

00:26:04.567 --> 00:26:06.400
and there's always a
lot of noise around us,

00:26:06.400 --> 00:26:08.350
people are always
walking around,

00:26:08.350 --> 00:26:10.720
or you just hear
conversations from people who

00:26:10.720 --> 00:26:12.720
are sitting right next to you.

00:26:12.720 --> 00:26:14.650
Yeah, do you have, I
guess, recommendations

00:26:14.650 --> 00:26:17.530
for how to sort of carve out
that time for yourself, even

00:26:17.530 --> 00:26:18.605
in that environment?

00:26:18.605 --> 00:26:21.760
MORRA AARONS-MELE: Yeah,
that's Chapter 10 in the book.

00:26:21.760 --> 00:26:24.790
And to be honest, you
know, I think that it's

00:26:24.790 --> 00:26:26.260
a very individual thing.

00:26:26.260 --> 00:26:27.150
I hear you.

00:26:27.150 --> 00:26:28.930
I hear you on the open plan.

00:26:28.930 --> 00:26:32.650
I think that more companies--
and I don't know about Google,

00:26:32.650 --> 00:26:35.350
and I'd actually be
very curious to know--

00:26:35.350 --> 00:26:37.220
are building in
more private space,

00:26:37.220 --> 00:26:41.230
especially with the rise
of pod based set ups

00:26:41.230 --> 00:26:45.670
and sort of agile
everything where there is so

00:26:45.670 --> 00:26:48.700
much collaborating happening.

00:26:48.700 --> 00:26:52.414
I think people also understand
that individual teams might

00:26:52.414 --> 00:26:53.830
want a quiet space
to collaborate,

00:26:53.830 --> 00:26:55.820
but that people need a break.

00:26:55.820 --> 00:26:57.430
We're all over meetinged.

00:26:57.430 --> 00:27:01.080
I also think the rise of Slack,
and I guess here you use Gchat,

00:27:01.080 --> 00:27:03.460
but you know, the constant
communicating not just

00:27:03.460 --> 00:27:06.790
face-to-face, but online
while we're sitting publicly,

00:27:06.790 --> 00:27:08.450
is very draining.

00:27:08.450 --> 00:27:12.850
I think if you can, and you
are able to do your best work,

00:27:12.850 --> 00:27:16.600
talking to your
manager, and you know,

00:27:16.600 --> 00:27:18.670
if working from
home is your thing,

00:27:18.670 --> 00:27:22.240
if there's a quieter place,
I think many of us are

00:27:22.240 --> 00:27:25.330
socialized-- and I
totally understand it--

00:27:25.330 --> 00:27:28.090
to be afraid to ask for what we
need to get our best job done.

00:27:28.090 --> 00:27:31.090
But I have some amazing
statistics in the book.

00:27:31.090 --> 00:27:33.487
Your boss will accommodate
you, because she

00:27:33.487 --> 00:27:34.570
doesn't want you to leave.

00:27:34.570 --> 00:27:37.590
It's very expensive and it's
a major pain in the butt.

00:27:37.590 --> 00:27:41.230
And so being prepared, having
a plan, and saying, you know,

00:27:41.230 --> 00:27:43.660
I have to get this project done.

00:27:43.660 --> 00:27:44.710
I need quiet.

00:27:44.710 --> 00:27:47.350
I will do my best
work in the quiet.

00:27:47.350 --> 00:27:49.930
I'm going to take
three hours on Friday.

00:27:49.930 --> 00:27:51.400
You have my cell phone.

00:27:51.400 --> 00:27:54.600
I'm going to be on
Gchat, and just trying

00:27:54.600 --> 00:27:57.390
a little bit of a
pilot and easing in

00:27:57.390 --> 00:27:58.590
might be really effective.

00:27:58.590 --> 00:28:03.630
But I think not being afraid
to say, we all feel that way.

00:28:03.630 --> 00:28:05.610
It is a very
draining environment,

00:28:05.610 --> 00:28:08.242
and so don't be ashamed.

00:28:08.242 --> 00:28:09.700
AUDIENCE: Thanks
