00:33:08.369 --> 00:33:09.160
It's all open plan.

00:33:09.160 --> 00:33:10.785
So one of the senior
engineers actually

00:33:10.785 --> 00:33:12.930
had a bit of a palace
coup and insisted

00:33:12.930 --> 00:33:15.460
he have his own building
with private spaces built.

00:33:15.460 --> 00:33:18.210
I don't know if that's true
or not, but I was like, yes.

00:33:18.210 --> 00:33:21.180
So if I had one dream
for workplaces to change,

00:33:21.180 --> 00:33:26.550
it would be that managers stop
looking at the person who's

00:33:26.550 --> 00:33:30.570
always in the office as
their most ambitious person,

00:33:30.570 --> 00:33:34.020
and look at the person
who does the best work.

00:33:34.020 --> 00:33:42.330
I feel that, again, we equate
face time, seeming enthusiasm,

00:33:42.330 --> 00:33:46.890
team spirit, all this stuff
with ambition and skill,

00:33:46.890 --> 00:33:50.340
and that's actually
not the case at all.

00:33:50.340 --> 00:33:53.160
If I could have grown
through the corporate ladder

00:33:53.160 --> 00:33:55.260
and worked from home
two mornings a week,

00:33:55.260 --> 00:33:56.790
I would have been really happy.

00:33:56.790 --> 00:34:00.570
So I would like people to
stop, to decouple ambition

00:34:00.570 --> 00:34:04.035
from face time, and
certainly from extroversion.

00:34:04.035 --> 00:34:05.420
AUDIENCE: I was going to say--

00:34:05.420 --> 00:34:07.753
I don't if this is a question
or a response to something

00:34:07.753 --> 00:34:12.610
that somebody else asked, but
are you familiar with "Rest"

00:34:12.610 --> 00:34:14.642
by Alex Pang.

00:34:14.642 --> 00:34:16.600
MORRA AARONS-MELE: Yes,
I quote it in the book.

00:34:16.600 --> 00:34:21.130
AUDIENCE: Yeah, because he talks
a bit about many intellectuals

00:34:21.130 --> 00:34:23.365
or quiet people or
whatever who, you know,

00:34:23.365 --> 00:34:26.739
would do an hour or
two of work, and then

00:34:26.739 --> 00:34:29.537
go out on a walk for an
hour, hour and a half,

00:34:29.537 --> 00:34:30.370
something like that.

00:34:30.370 --> 00:34:33.190
And to me, I have
certainly done that here

00:34:33.190 --> 00:34:35.380
at Google when I need
quiet time by myself

00:34:35.380 --> 00:34:36.611
to think about something.

00:34:36.611 --> 00:34:38.860
The problem is, you can't
bring like a laptop with you

00:34:38.860 --> 00:34:39.610
and type.

00:34:39.610 --> 00:34:42.100
But around here,
sometimes that's

00:34:42.100 --> 00:34:46.767
the only time you can
get quiet for 30 minutes.

00:34:46.767 --> 00:34:48.850
MORRA AARONS-MELE: I just
want to acknowledge that

00:34:48.850 --> 00:34:51.469
and to say, again,
it sounds so basic,

00:34:51.469 --> 00:34:55.210
but the ability to
claim your time to think

00:34:55.210 --> 00:34:57.066
is really powerful.

00:34:57.066 --> 00:34:58.940
And I know that Google's
always been a leader

00:34:58.940 --> 00:35:00.023
and that you've had your--

00:35:00.023 --> 00:35:01.390
is it 20% rule, or whatever?

00:35:01.390 --> 00:35:05.020
But you know, so few
places in our life

00:35:05.020 --> 00:35:09.530
give us a moment to be with
our thoughts and get creative.

00:35:09.530 --> 00:35:14.505
And that's a discipline at
work that we need to honor.

00:35:14.505 --> 00:35:15.880
AUDIENCE: I had
another question.

00:35:15.880 --> 00:35:16.560
MORRA AARONS-MELE: Sure.

00:35:16.560 --> 00:35:18.601
AUDIENCE: Since you brought
up Hilary's campaign,

00:35:18.601 --> 00:35:19.719
I was curious--

00:35:19.719 --> 00:35:21.260
yeah, I guess if
you were going to do

00:35:21.260 --> 00:35:24.234
that, having those [INAUDIBLE]
conversations, how would you

00:35:24.234 --> 00:35:27.470
have gone about, I guess,
like changing the way that she

00:35:27.470 --> 00:35:29.960
sort of went across America
and had these conversations?

00:35:29.960 --> 00:35:31.535
MORRA AARONS-MELE:
Oh, so politics.

00:35:31.535 --> 00:35:33.170
AUDIENCE: I'm just curious.

00:35:33.170 --> 00:35:34.420
Yeah, it's not really like a--

00:35:34.420 --> 00:35:37.086
MORRA AARONS-MELE: No, you know,
I have been thinking about this

00:35:37.086 --> 00:35:39.500
because as a sort of digital
political consultant,

00:35:39.500 --> 00:35:43.460
I've been thinking, and there's
actually a candidate running--

00:35:43.460 --> 00:35:45.466
you should check
out, Laura Moser,

00:35:45.466 --> 00:35:47.840
in Texas-- who started something
called the daily action,

00:35:47.840 --> 00:35:49.644
which is online action.

00:35:49.644 --> 00:35:50.810
She's a bit of an introvert.

00:35:50.810 --> 00:35:53.830
So I'm going see
how she's running.

00:35:53.830 --> 00:35:57.920
Again, I think that we don't
always get the best candidates,

00:35:57.920 --> 00:36:01.700
because so much of
being a politician

00:36:01.700 --> 00:36:04.250
is that glad
handling small talk.

00:36:04.250 --> 00:36:07.010
I mean, if we think walking into
a tech networking event is bad,

00:36:07.010 --> 00:36:11.000
imagine walking into a firehouse
dinner in a different state,

00:36:11.000 --> 00:36:12.260
firehouse breakfast every--

00:36:12.260 --> 00:36:15.470
I mean, oh my gosh, that's
hell for an introvert.

00:36:15.470 --> 00:36:20.540
So I would love to see
candidates win who could either

00:36:20.540 --> 00:36:22.550
use online conversations.

00:36:22.550 --> 00:36:24.200
You know, wouldn't
it be amazing if you

00:36:24.200 --> 00:36:27.080
could have Skype
conversations, if you could

00:36:27.080 --> 00:36:29.180
use all these tools
to connect with people

00:36:29.180 --> 00:36:32.480
in a meaningful way,
convene smaller groups.

00:36:32.480 --> 00:36:34.190
Usually small groups are just--

00:36:34.190 --> 00:36:38.060
only high donors get small
groups now, high dollar donors.

00:36:38.060 --> 00:36:40.040
And yet, politicians
are expected

00:36:40.040 --> 00:36:42.420
to be so extroverted
at the detriment

00:36:42.420 --> 00:36:43.489
to the skill of policy.

00:36:43.489 --> 00:36:45.780
I think this is something
we're all going to deal with.

00:36:45.780 --> 00:36:49.820
We're dealing with diversity
at work, work styles.

00:36:49.820 --> 00:36:53.060
We're dealing with failed
styles of leadership.

00:36:53.060 --> 00:36:56.300
I think we need to rethink all
of our different temperaments

00:36:56.300 --> 00:37:00.290
and how leaders can be different
kinds of people to your point,

00:37:00.290 --> 00:37:02.830
and that that will happen in
the next five or 10 years.

00:37:02.830 --> 00:37:06.010
DAVID: Well, here's to seeing
how the future accommodates

00:37:06.010 --> 00:37:07.135
and how introverts adapt.

00:37:07.135 --> 00:37:08.260
MORRA AARONS-MELE: Ah, yes.

00:37:08.260 --> 00:37:09.970
DAVID: Thank you
